1 Problem 1.

In general, people experience a decline in cognitive function with age. Dementia is defined as serious cognitive decline that impacts everyday activities. People with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) are generally able to perform daily activities, but have greater decline in cognitive function than in typical aging. Many people with MCI eventually develop Alzheimer’s Disease or other types of dementia.

We will use a dataset containing an imaging biomarker, a genetic biomarker, and demographic information, defined below. The dataset (MCI.RData) contains data related to the Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (http://adni.loni.usc.edu/tadpole-challenge-dataset-available/). Parts of the data have been simulated in order to allow data sharing for educational purposes. Qualitatively, the results you discover in this educational dataset are likely to be the same as in the unaltered dataset.

Variable Codebook:

  1. ID Participant identifier.

  2. VISIT Visit time in months since baseline.

  3. DX

  • 0 = normal aging
  • 1 = MCI

  1. AGE_VISIT Participant’s age at the time of the visit.

  2. PTGENDER Participant gender.

  • Female
  • Male

  1. PTEDUCAT Total years of education.

  2. APOE4 Numeric variable equal to 0, 1, or 2 indicating the individual has 0, 1, or 2 copies of the E4 allele of apolipoprotein. This genetic variant is linked to the formation of amyloid beta deposits in the brain, which is one of the characteristics of Alzheimer’s Disease.

  3. HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL Volume of the right plus left hippocampus in mm^3. The hippocampus is a subcortical gray matter structure in the brain that is associated with memory.

We will subset to cross-sectional data. We do this for educational purposes, as we want to fit variants of the model a few times to understand the effects of different spline specifications. It takes a long time to fit the longitudinal gam. So for this homework, it is easier to work with the cross-sectional data. Please note that in your own research projects and future jobs, you will of course want to use all of your data.

Create the cross-sectional dataset and convert hippocampus volume to cm^3:

load("MCI.RData")
mcidata$HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL=mcidata$HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL/1000
mcidata$APOE4 = factor(mcidata$APOE4)
mcidata = mcidata[complete.cases(mcidata),]
mcidata_cx = mcidata[!duplicated(mcidata$ID),]

1.1

Using mathematical notation, with \(g_j(x_{ij})\) for smooth terms, write out a statistical model with normal errors for the cross-sectional data with \(y_i\) denoting hippocampus volume in cm^3 and the covariates DX, PTGENDER, APOE4 (treating APOE4 as a factor with reference level 0), a smooth for AGE_VISIT, and a smooth for PTEDUCAT. Include distributional assumptions. (You do not need to write the basis functions used for the smooth terms \(g_j(x_{ij})\), nor the penalized objective function.)

\[ \begin{aligned} y_i = &\beta_0 + \beta_1 * I(DX_i = 0) + \beta_2 * I(PTGENDER_i = Male) + \beta_3 * I(APOE4_i = 1) + \beta_4 * I(APOE4_i = 2) \\ & + g_1({AGE\_VISIT}_i) + g_2({PTEDUCAT}_i) + \epsilon_i \end{aligned} \] where \(\epsilon_i \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0, \sigma^2)\).

1.2

Fit this model using mgcv::gam. Use all defaults. Print the output of summary.

library(mgcv)
## Loading required package: nlme
## This is mgcv 1.8-41. For overview type 'help("mgcv-package")'.
model1.2 <- gam(HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL ~ DX + PTGENDER + APOE4 + s(AGE_VISIT) + s(PTEDUCAT), data = mcidata_cx)

Create diagnostic plots using gam.check(). Briefly comment on each of the four plots. Are there any issues?

gam.check(model1.2)

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The first plot is the QQ plot of deviance residuals. The data does not deviate too much from the straight line, suggesting that the normality assumption is not violated.

The second plot is the residuals vs. linear predictor plot. The residuals appear to be randomly scattered around zero, indicating that the model may be adequate for capturing the underlying relationship of the data and the homoscedasticity assumption is not violated.

The third plot is the histogram of residuals. The distribution of residuals looks very similar to the standard normal distribution, indicating that our normality assumption is not violated.

The fourth plot is response vs. fitted value plot. The fitted values appear to be strongly linearly correlated with response, indicating that the current model adequately fits the data.

1.4

State the null hypothesis for each p-value in the spline basis dimension diagnostics in gam.check(). Then state whether it is accepted or rejected at \(\alpha=0.05\).

For AGE_VISIT, \(H_0\): The basis dimension k = 10 for AGE_VISIT is adequate. The p-value is greater than our \(\alpha = 0.05\). We fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the basis dimension k = 10 is adequate for AGE_VISIT.

For PTEDUCAT, \(H_0\): The basis dimension k = 10 for PTEDUCAT is adequate. The p-value is smaller than our \(\alpha = 0.05\). We reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the basis dimension k = 10 might be insufficient for PTEDUCAT.

1.5

Next, inspect the effective degrees of freedom versus k’ in gam.check(). Does this approach suggest that k is adequate?

The effective degrees of freedom are 2.05 and 1.94 for AGE_VISIT and PTEDUCAT, respectively, which are much smaller than k’ = 9. These suggest that k = 10 is adequate.

1.25

In words, describe how the effect of age is modified by APOE4.

For people with age < 65, compared to APOE4= 0 or 1, the hippocampal volume decreases more rapidly for people with APOE4= 2, such that hippocampal volume is lower in APOE4=2 at age = 70 than for APOE4=0 or 1. For people with age > 70, compared to APOE4= 0 or 1, hippocampal volume decreases less rapidly for people with APOE4= 2, with hippocampal volumes being more similar in the three groups at age=85.

1.26

Conduct an approximate F test for the interaction between APOE4 and the smooth for AGE_VISIT in the gam. Report the F-statistic, DF numerator and denominator, p-value, and your conclusion.

anova(model1.14, model1.20, test='F')
## Analysis of Deviance Table
##

##     APOE4

## 1    847.24     767.56

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The F-statistic is 2.0402. DF numerator is 8.8111, and denominator is 847.24. The p-value is 0.03368 < 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis, and conclude that the effect of age is significantly modified by APOE4.

1.27

Fit a linear model (no smooth terms) with the same terms and report the F-statistic, DF numerator and denominator, pvalue, and your conclusion according to this linear model for the interaction between APOE4 and AGE_VISIT.

model1.27_inter = lm(HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL~DX+PTGENDER+APOE4+
                      PTEDUCAT+AGE_VISIT*APOE4, 
                      data=mcidata_cx)
model1.27_no_inter = lm(HIPPOCAMPUS_VOL~DX+PTGENDER+APOE4+

The F-statistic is 0.4385. DF numerator is 2, and denominator is 849. The p-value is 0.6452, greater than our \(\alpha\) = 0.05. Therefore, we do not have enough evidence to conclude that the effect of age is significantly modified by APOE4.
